{
  "answer": "**In Cynewulf's *Elene*, Constantine does not specifically ask anyone for the meaning of the cross-vision.** Instead, the heavenly messenger who appears to him in a dream directly reveals and explains its significance, addressing him by name, telling him to \"fear not this foe\" and to recognize the cross (the \"bright beacon\" or \"victory-tree\") as a \"salvation-token,\" with the words of victory inscribed upon it: \"By this sign, conquer.\"[^1] The emperor awakens with understanding, his sorrow lifted, and immediately orders his craftsmen to replicate the symbol as a banner (a \"standard... fashioned as the Rood\").[^2]\n\nNo other passage depicts Constantine questioning the vision's meaning—he receives divine interpretation on the spot, and the narrative soon shifts to Elene's quest without him raising further inquiry.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-306e06).\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-86294a).\n[^3]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-acdc07).",
